  "prompt": "Does four wheel drive consume more fuel than two wheel drive?",
  "response": "Yes, four-wheel drive (4WD) typically consumes more fuel than two-wheel drive (2WD). This is because 4WD systems engage all four wheels, which increases the mechanical resistance and friction within the drivetrain, leading to higher fuel consumption. Additionally, 4WD vehicles are often heavier due to the added components, which can also contribute to increased fuel use.\n\nHowever, the difference in fuel efficiency can vary depending on several factors:\n\n1. **Driving Conditions**: In slippery or off-road conditions, 4WD can provide better traction and might be more efficient in those specific scenarios. But for regular road use, 2WD is generally more fuel-efficient.\n\n2. **Type of 4WD System**: Some modern 4WD systems, like those with part-time or on-demand settings, can switch between 2WD and 4WD modes. When in 2WD mode, these vehicles can be as fuel-efficient as dedicated 2WD vehicles.\n\n3. **Vehicle Design**: Some vehicles are designed to be more fuel-efficient overall, regardless of whether they are 2WD or 4WD. Advances in technology and engineering can mitigate some of the fuel consumption differences.\n\n4. **Driver Behavior**: Aggressive driving, frequent acceleration, and high speeds can exacerbate the fuel consumption difference between 2WD and 4WD.\n\nIn summary, while 4WD generally uses more fuel than 2WD, the actual difference can be influenced by various factors, and modern technology is continually working to narrow this gap.",
